+ <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas Swanson ,Knight was born in 1350, in London, England, United Kingdom, his father, Tim Jackson, was 45 and his mother, Margaret Jackson, was 52. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Nicholas Swanson. He died in 1400, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1350–1400":"1350–1400","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1376–1470":"1376–1470","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1298–1354":"1298–1354","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1298":"1298","1350":"1350","1470":"1470","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Christ Church, Southwark, London, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Southwark, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–1400":"1350–1400","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1376–1470":"1376–1470","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1298–1354":"1298–1354","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1298":"1298","1350":"1350","1470":"1470","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Christ Church, Southwark, London, Surrey, England, United